description: {"blocks":[{"key":"crdf5","text":"It is difficult to see in the image (this is heavily diluted gDNA), but this protocol does effectively remove small DNA fragments if you, for example, wanted to remove them prior to preparing Illumina sequencing libraries. I saw this protocol using various NaCl concentrations and different types of PEG:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cmug2","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"7ua82","text":"My lab (Marine Gene Probe Lab, Dalhousie University) has PEG-8000 and a previous article I read (J.L. Hartley, H. Bowen, PEG precipitation for selective removal of small DNA fragments, have not managed to find this online) tested a 6.7% PEG-8000 solution against MgCl2. Oddly enough, when I tested their protocol I didn't get any DNA back at all but I did when I used NaCl at Tyson's concentrations. Huh. Go figure.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4l5nr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"aabng","text":"Anyway, I tested four different concentrations of NaCl (450mM, 475mM, 500mM, and 525mM) with 6.7% PEG 8000 in a 25ul reaction. 5ul of this was a ratio of 5M NaCl to 1X TE adjusted to get the aforementioned final concentrations. Another 5ul was 33.5% PEG 8000. Then 15ul of the DNA you want to size select (if you don't have enough, top up with 1X TE). 450mM seems to work the best for precipitating out the HMW band while minimizing the smear, but I have not re-tested this with more concentrated DNA. The 5M NaCl/1X TE ratios (in ul) for the different concentrations are:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4618t","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a7rqk","text":"Conc:     (NaCl/1X TE)","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9},{"style":"bold","offset":10,"length":12}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fgkp0","text":"450mM (2.25/2.75)","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6s1sb","text":"475mM (2.5/2.5)","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"h479","text":"500mM (2.75/2.25)","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3r3a0","text":"525mM (3/2)","type":"align-left","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8r9dt","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6suav","text":"This test was done using gDNA extracted from Three-Spine Stickleback (Gasterosteus aculeatus) which was 1/5 diluted for this test... after being topped up with 10ul 1X TE beforehand. That's why the gel is so faint and why I'm a bit concerned that the 450mM may also be losing HMW DNA. I may re-test this in the future.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"citation","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"align":"","authors":"John Tyson","can_edit":true,"date":0,"doi":"https://protocols.io/view/size-selective-precipitation-of-dna-using-peg-amp-7erhjd6","guid":"9504BDD070B911EDA610057FBCBF6272","id":0,"journal":"protocols.io","protocol_id":27825,"title":"Size Selective Precipitation of DNA using PEG \u0026 Salt"}}}}
disclaimer: {"blocks":[{"key":"6robc","text":"This is not published work and is basically just me messing with other protocols to see what happens.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
